def grayscale(img):
    """Applies the Grayscale transform"""
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)

def weighted_img(img, initial_img, =0.8, =1., =0.):
    """
    `img` is the output of the hough_lines(), An image with lines drawn on it.
    Should be a blank image (all black) with lines drawn on it.
    
    `initial_img` should be the image before any processing.
    
    The result image is computed as follows:
    
    initial_img *  + img *  + 
    NOTE: initial_img and img must be the same shape!
    """
    return cv2.addWeighted(initial_img, , img, , )
 
def yellow_enhance(img):
    '''
    enhanve the yellow color in image
    step1:convert rgb to hsv
    step2:create a lower/upper range of hsv
    step3:create a mask
    '''
    img_hsv = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
    lower_yellow = np.array([20, 100, 100], dtype = "uint8")
    upper_yellow = np.array([30, 255, 255], dtype = "uint8")    
    mask_yellow = cv2.inRange(img_hsv,lower_yellow,upper_yellow)
    return weighted_img(mask_yellow,grayscale(img),=1., =1., =0.)

def gaussian_blur(img, kernel_size):
    """Applies a Gaussian Noise kernel"""
    return cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (kernel_size, kernel_size), 0)

def canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold):
    """Applies the Canny transform"""
    return cv2.Canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold)


# grayscale the image
# gray_img = grayscale(image)
gray_img = yellow_enhance(image)

# define a kernel size and apply Gaussian smoothing
kernel_size = 5
blur_gray = gaussian_blur(gray_img,kernel_size)

# define our parameters for Canny and apply
low_threshold = 50
high_threshold = 150
edges_img = canny(blur_gray, low_threshold, high_threshold)

ROI segemation¶

In [4]:
def region_of_interest(img, vertices):
    """
    Applies an image mask.    
    Only keeps the region of the image defined by the polygon
    formed from `vertices`. The rest of the image is set to black.
    `vertices` should be a numpy array of integer points.
    """
    #defining a blank mask to start with
    mask = np.zeros_like(img)   
    
    #defining a 3 channel or 1 channel color to fill the mask with depending on the input image
    if len(img.shape) > 2:
        channel_count = img.shape[2]  # i.e. 3 or 4 depending on your image
        ignore_mask_color = (255,) * channel_count
    else:
        ignore_mask_color = 255
        
    #filling pixels inside the polygon defined by "vertices" with the fill color    
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, ignore_mask_color)
    
    #returning the image only where mask pixels are nonzero
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(img, mask)
    return masked_image

vertices = np.array([[(130,540),(410,330),(570,330),(910,540)]], dtype=np.int32)
masked_img = region_of_interest(edges_img,vertices)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,3))

Hough transform and line detection¶

In [5]:
def hough_lines(img, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_len, max_line_gap):
    """
    `img` should be the output of a Canny transform.
    """
    lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(img, rho, theta, threshold, np.array([]), minLineLength=min_line_len, maxLineGap=max_line_gap)
    return lines
# Define the Hough transform parameters
# Make a blank the same size as our image to draw on
rho = 1 # distance resolution in pixels of the Hough grid
theta = np.pi/180 # angular resolution in radians of the Hough grid
threshold = 30    # minimum number of votes (intersections in Hough grid cell)
min_line_length = 20 #minimum number of pixels making up a line
max_line_gap = 20    # maximum gap in pixels between connectable line segments

lines = hough_lines(masked_img, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_length, max_line_gap)

Draw the extrapolated/average lines to the image¶

In [6]:
def draw_lines(img, lines, color=[255, 0, 0], thickness=5):
    """
    Applies extrapolated lines to the image based on the slope of detected lines.
    """
      
    # y-axis coordinates to which the line will be extrapolated to
    ymin = img.shape[0]
    ymax = img.shape[0]
        
    # left lane lines
    left_slope_all = []
    left_y_all = []
    left_x_all = []
        
    # right lane lines
    right_slope_all = []
    right_y_all = []
    right_x_all = []
                        
    # group the detected lines
    for line in lines:
        for x1,y1,x2,y2 in line:
            slope, intercept = np.polyfit((x1,x2),(y1,y2),1)
            ymin = min(min(y1,y2), ymin)
            if (slope<0):
                left_slope_all += [slope]
                left_y_all += [y1,y2]
                left_x_all += [x1,x2]
            else:
                right_slope_all += [slope]
                right_y_all += [y1,y2]
                right_x_all += [x1,x2]
    # mean value
    left_slope_mean, right_slope_mean = np.mean(left_slope_all), np.mean(right_slope_all)
    left_x_mean, right_x_mean = np.mean(left_x_all), np.mean(right_x_all)
    left_y_mean, right_y_mean = np.mean(left_y_all), np.mean(right_y_all)
    left_intercept_mean = left_y_mean - left_x_mean*left_slope_mean
    right_intercept_mean = right_y_mean - right_x_mean*right_slope_mean
    
    # draw extrapolated lane line
    line_image = np.copy(img)*0
    # make sure we have some point in each lane line group
    if (len(left_slope_all) > 0) and (len(right_slope_all) > 0):
        # left line 
        left_x_start =  int((ymax-left_intercept_mean)/left_slope_mean)
        left_x_end =  int((ymin-left_intercept_mean)/left_slope_mean)
        cv2.line(line_image, (left_x_start,int(ymax)), (left_x_end,int(ymin)), color, thickness)

        # right line
        right_x_start = int((ymin-right_intercept_mean)/right_slope_mean)  
        right_x_end = int((ymax-right_intercept_mean)/right_slope_mean)     
        cv2.line(line_image, (right_x_start,int(ymin)), (right_x_end,int(ymax)), color, thickness)
    extrapolated_img = cv2.addWeighted(img, 0.8, line_image, 1, 0)
    return extrapolated_img

extrapolated_img = draw_lines(image, lines)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,3))
plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.05, bottom=0.02, right=0.98, top=1, wspace=0.12, hspace=0)
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.title('Original')
plt.imshow(image)
plt.subplot(1,2,2)

plt.savefig('test_images_output/solidWhiteRight_lane.jpg', dpi=300)
plt.show()

Build a lane finding pipeline¶

In [7]:
# pipeline for lane line detection in video
def process_image(image):
    # Grayscale the image
    gray_img = yellow_enhance(image)
    #gray_img = grayscale(image)
    
    # Define a kernel size and apply Gaussian smoothing
    kernel_size = 5
    blur_gray = gaussian_blur(gray_img,kernel_size)

    # Define our parameters for Canny and apply
    low_threshold = 50
    high_threshold = 150
    edges_img = canny(blur_gray, low_threshold, high_threshold)
    
    # ROI
    vertices = np.array([[(0,540),(460,320),(500,320),(960,540)]], dtype=np.int32)
    masked_img = region_of_interest(edges_img,vertices)
    
    # hough and lines
    rho = 2 
    theta = np.pi/180 
    threshold = 15     
    min_line_length = 40 
    max_line_gap = 20    

    lines = hough_lines(masked_img, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_length, max_line_gap)
   
    # extrapolated lines
    extrapolated_img = draw_lines(image, lines)
    
    return extrapolated_img

import os
test_imgs = os.listdir("test_images/")

imgs = []
extrapolated_imgs = []

for file in test_imgs:
    img = mpimg.imread("test_images/"+file)
    imgs.append(img)
    extrapolated_img = process_image(img)
    extrapolated_imgs.append(extrapolated_img)
    plt.figure(num=file,figsize=(8,3))
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.05, bottom=0.02, right=0.98, top=1, wspace=0.12, hspace=0)
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.title('Origianl')
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.title('Lane line')
    plt.imshow(extrapolated_img)
    plt.savefig('test_images_output/'+file, dpi=300)
    plt.show()
